Algorithms - Part 02

Tree-Based Models

  • These involving stratifying the predictor space;

  • Rule to prediction: use the mean or mode;

  • These types of approaches are known as decisions tree methods;

  • Decision trees are simple and useful for interpretations;

  • Bagging, Random Forest and Boosting;

Tree-based Models: Decision Trees

  • Decision Tree can be applied to regression and classification;

  • The process of building a regression tree comprises two steps:

  1. Divide the predictor space into \(J\) distinct and non-overlapping regions \(R_1, R_2, ..., R_J\);
  2. For every obs that falls into the region \(R_j\), we make the same prediction;

Tree-based Models: Decision Trees

  • How do we contruct the \(R_1, ..., R_J\)?

  • The goal is to find \(R_1, ..., R_J\) such as \[ min \sum_{j = 1}^J \sum_{i \in R_j} (y_i - \hat{y}_{R_j})^2 \]

  • Unfortunately, it is computationally infeasible;

  • Better approach: top-down, greedy approach known as recursive binary splitting;

Tree-based Models: Decision Trees

  • Recursive binary splitting:
    • top-down beacuse it begins at the top of the three;
    • greddy because at each step the split is made at that particular step;
  • The algorithm:
  1. Select the predictor \(X_j\) and the cutpoint \(s\);
  2. Split the predictor space in two regions \[ R_1 = \{X|X_j \lt s\} \quad\text{and}\quad R_2 = \{X|X_j \lt s\} \] such as leads to the greatest reduction in \[ \sum_{i : x_i \in R_1} (y_i - \hat{y}_{R_1})^2 + \sum_{i : x_i \in R_2} (y_i - \hat{y}_{R_2})^2 \]
  3. Repeat the above process but this time using the identified regions;
  4. The process continues until a stopping criteria is reached.

Tree-based Models: Decision Tree

  • The process described may produce very good prediction on the training set;

  • Likely to overfit the test set;

  • Possible alternative: build the tree so long as the decrease in RSS exceeds some threshold;

  • That is, grow a very large tree \(T_0\) and then prune it back to obtain a subtree \(T\);

  • Cost complexity prunning solves our problem;

  • Consider a sequence of trees indexed by a tunning parameter \(\alpha\);

  • For each value of \(\alpha\) there correspond a subtree \(T \subset T_0\) such that

\[ \sum_{m = 1}^T \sum_{i: x_i \in R_m}(y_i - \hat{y}_{R_m})^2 + \alpha|T| \] is a small as possible;

  • \(\alpha\) is a tunning parameter controlling the trade-off between subtrees complexity and fit to the dataset.

Tree-based Models: Decision Tree

  • The Final Algorithm:
  1. Use recursive binary splitting to grow a large tree;
  2. Apply Cost complexity prunning in order to obtain a subtree as a function of \(\alpha\);
  3. Repeat Steps 1 and 2 for different values of \(\alpha\);
  4. Return the subtree from Step 3 that gives the best out-of-sample performance.

Tree-based Models: Decision Tree

  • What about classification settings?

  • Almost the same process. In general, two different things:

  1. prediction: majority vote;
  2. Loss function: not RSS anymore;
  • Classification error rate: \[E = 1 - max_k(\hat{p}_{mk})\]
  • Gini Index: \[G = \sum_{k = 1}^K\hat{p}_{mk}(1 - \hat{p}_{mk})\]
  • Cross-entropy: \[ D = - \sum_{k = 1}^K \hat{p}_{mk}\log\hat{p}_{mk} \]

Tree-based Models: Bagging

  • Remember that decision trees suffer from high variance;

  • Some of the most important properties an estimator can enjoy are:

    • Unbiasedness: \(E(\hat{\theta}) = \theta\)
    • Consistency: \(\hat{\theta} \stackrel{p}{\longrightarrow} \theta\)

Tree-based Models: Bagging

  • The Weak Law of Large Numbers:

Let \(Z_1, ..., Z_B\) a iid sequence of random variables and such as \(E(Z_t) = \mu\) and \(var(Z_t) = \sigma^2 < \infty\). Let \(\overline{Z_B} = B^{-1} \sum_{b=1}^B Z_b\) be an estimator for the unknown \(\mu\).

\[ \lim_{B \rightarrow \infty} E(\overline{Z_B}) = \frac{1}{B} \sum_{b = 1}^T \mu = \mu \] and

\[ \lim_{B \rightarrow \infty} var(\overline{Z_B}) = \lim_{B \rightarrow \infty} B^{-2}\sum_{b = 1}^T var(Z_b) = B^{-2} \sigma^2 \rightarrow 0 \] then,

\[ \overline{Z_B} = \frac{1}{B} \sum_{b = 1}^T Z_b \stackrel{p}{\longrightarrow} \mu. \]

Tree-based Models: Bagging

  • Thats when bootstrap comes at hand!!;

  • Bootstrap is an extremely powerful idea;

  • It is a computer-based method for assessing the accuracy of statistical estimates;

  • Main Idea:

  1. Treat the data as if they were the (true, unknown) population;
  2. Draw sample (with replacement) from the data;
  3. Repeate the procedure \(B\) times, each time computing the quantity of interest;
  4. Use the \(B\) values to estimate its unknown distribution;

  • Boostratp aggregation or bagging is a general purpose procedure for reducing the variance;

  • In other words, we could calculate \(\hat{f}_1(x), \hat{f}_2(x), ..., \hat{f}_B(x)\) using \(B\) training sets then average the resulting predictions;

  • Bagging has been demonstrated by give impressive improvements performance over individual decision trees;

Tree-based Models: Random Forest

  • Random Forest provides an improvement over bagged trees;

  • Small tweak that decorrelates the trees;

  • When building decision tree, a random sample of \(m\) predictors;

  • Typicall we choose \(m \approx \sqrt{P}\);

  • In other words, at each split in the tree the algorith is not even allowed to consider all \(P\);

  • Rationale:

    • Suppose there is one very predictor, along with number of moderately ones;
    • Then, in the collection of bagged, most or all of trees will use this strong predictor;
    • As a result, the predictions will be highly correlated;
    • Unfornately, averaging many highly correlated trees does not lead to large reduction in variance;

  • Random Forest forces each split to consider only a subset of the predictors;

  • The main difference between Bagging and Random Forest is the choice of \(m\);

  • \(m\) is tunning parameter.

Tree-based Models: Boosting

  • Boosting is a general approach;

  • Bagging involves creating multiple copies of data using bootstrap, fitting a separete tree and then combining them by averaging;

  • In Boosting, trees are grown sequentially: each tree is grown using information from previously tree;

  • Boosting DOES NOT involve bootstrap. Rather, each tree is fit on a modified version of training data;

  • The idea of Boosting is to combine several weak learners into a stronger one;

Tree-based Models: Boosting

  • Boosting algorithm:
  1. Set \(\hat{f}(x) = 0\) and \(\epsilon_i = y_i\) for all \(i\) in training set;
  2. For \(b = 1, ..., B\), repeat:
    1. Fit a tree \(\hat{f}^b\) to the training set \((X, \epsilon)\);
    2. Update \(\hat{f}\) by adding in a shruken version of the new tree: \[ \hat{f}(x) \longleftarrow \hat{f}(x) + \lambda\hat{f}^b(x) \]
    3. Update the residuals: \[ \epsilon_i \longleftarrow \epsilon_i - \lambda\hat{f}^b(x_i) \]
  3. Output the boosted model: \[ \hat{f}(x) = \sum_{b = 1}^B \lambda \hat{f}^b(x) \]

Tree-based Models: Boosting

  • The boosting approach learns slowly;

\[ \hat{f}(x) = \sum_{b = 1}^B \lambda \hat{f}^b(x) \]

  • In general, algorithm that learn slowly tend to perform well;

  • Unlike bagging, the number the construction of tree depends strongly on \(B\);

  • In general, Boosting has three tunning parameters:

  1. The number of trees \(B\): boosting can overfit if \(B\) is too large;
  2. The shrinkage parameter \(\lambda\): this controls the rate at which boosting learns;
  3. The number of \(d\) splits in each tree: this control the complexity of the tree.

Tree-based Models: Boosting

  • There are some boosting implementations:
  1. Adaptive Boosting (AdaBoost): this algorithm corrects its predecessor by increasing the weight of the misclassified training instances;
  2. Gradient Boosting (GBM): this method tries to fit the new predictor to the residual errors made by the previous predictor;
  3. XGboost: this algorithm has high predictive power and is ten times faster than any other gradient boosting techniques;
  4. Lightgbm: for datasets which are extremely large Light Gradient Boosting takes less time to run;
  5. Catboost: improvements over some existing libraries;

Support Vector Machine

  • Support Vector Machine (SVM) is a generalization of a simple classifier: maximal margin classifier;

  • SVM is an algorithm developed in the computer science communinity in 1990s;

  • Based on hyperplanes;

  • In a \(p\)-dimension, a hyperplane is a subspace of dimension \(p-1\);

  • The mathematical definition of a hyperplane:

\[ \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + ... + \beta_p X_p = 0 \quad (1) \]

  • For any \(\mathbb{X} = (X_1, ..., X_p)^T\) for which equation (1) holds;

  • Suppose \(X\) does does not satisfy (1):

\[ \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + ... + \beta_p X_p > 0 \\ \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + ... + \beta_p X_p < 0 \]

Classification using Hyperplane

  • Suppose \(\mathbb{X}\) with dimension \(N\)x\(P\) and \(Y = \{-1, 1\}\);

  • Suppose that an test obs \(x^* = (x_1, ..., x_P)^T\);

  • Suppose it is possible to construct a hyperplane separating training obs into classes;

  • This separating hyperplane would have the following rule:

\[ \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + ... + \beta_p x_{ip} > 0 \quad if \quad y_i = 1 \]

and

\[ \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + ... + \beta_p x_{ip} < 0 \quad if \quad y_i = -1 \]

  • Equivalent to:

\[ y_i(\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + ... + \beta_p x_{ip}) > 0 \] - we classify the test obs \(x^*\) based on the sign of \(f(x^*)\):

\[ f(x^*) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x^*_{i1} + ... + \beta_p x^*_{ip} \]

Maximal Margin Classifier

  • In general, if our data can be perfectly separated using a hyperplane;

  • There will in fact exist an infinite number of such hyperplanes;

  • maximal margin hyperplane: hyperplane that is farthest from the training obs;

Maximal Margin Classifier

  • This is the maximal margin Classifier;

\[ \hat{\beta}_1, ..., \hat{\beta}_P = argmax_{\beta_1, ..., \beta_P} \quad M \\ \text{subject to} \sum_{j = 1}^P \beta_j^2 = 1 \\ y_i(\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + ... + \beta_p x_{ip}) \ge M \\ \]

  • Apply the rule based of the sign of
    \[\hat{f}(x^*) = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 x^*_{i1} + ... + \hat{\beta}_p x^*_{ip}\]

Non-separable case

  • Maximal margin classifier very simple, intuitive;

  • If a separating hyperplane exists;

Non-separable case

  • Extend the idea of hyperplane that almost separate the classes;

  • Does NOT perfectly separate the classes, in the interest of separate the most;

  • The generalization of maximal marging classifier : Support Vector Classifier;

  • Here, we allow some obs to be on the incorrect side of the marging, or even of the hyperplane;

Non-separable case

  • The hyperplane is chosen as

\[ \hat{\beta}_1, ..., \hat{\beta}_P = argmax_{\beta_1, ..., \beta_P} \quad M \\ \text{subject to} \sum_{j = 1}^P \beta_j^2 = 1 \\ y_i(\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + ... + \beta_p x_{ip}) \ge M(1 - \epsilon_i) \\ \epsilon_i \ge 0, \, \, \sum_{i = 1}^N \epsilon_i \le C \\ \]

\(C\) is a tunning parameters;

  • Once we solved this problem, we classify the test obs based on the sign of \(\hat{f}(x^*)\);

Non-separable case

Support Vector Machine

  • SVC is good approach if the boundary between classes is linear;

  • Support Vector Machine (SVM) is an extension of the SVC;

  • An extension is due to enlarging the space using Kernels;

  • The solution to previous optimizations problems involves inner products of obs;

  • Inner product: \[ \langle x_i, x_{i^{'}} \rangle = \sum_{j=1}^P x_{ij} x_{i^{'}j} \]

  • SVC can be represented as: \[ f(x) = \beta_0 + \sum_{i = 1}^N \alpha_i \langle x, x_i \rangle \]

SVM

  • Replace with a Kernel: \(K(x_i, x_{i^{'}j})\)

  • Polynomial Kernel of degree \(d\) : \[ K(x_i, x_{i^{'}j}) = \left(1 + \sum_{j = 1}^P x_{ij} x_{i^{'}j}\right)^d \]

  • Radial Kernel:

\[ K(x_i, x_{i^{'}j}) = \exp\left( - \gamma \sum_{j = 1}^P (x_{ij} - x_{i^{'}j})^2\right) \]

Introduction to Deep Learning

What is deep learning?

What is deep learning?

The “deep” in deep learning

  • Deep learning is a specific subfield of machine learning;

  • The deep is not a reference to any king of deeper understand;

  • It is an idea of successive layers of representations;

  • These layered representations are learned via models called neural network;

  • Deep learning models ARE NOT models of the brain;

  • It is a mathematical framework for learning representation from data.

Getting started with neural networks

  • The anatomy of a Neural Network consisting in
  1. Input Layer: Thats our matrix of features \(\mathbf{X}\);
  2. Hidden Layer: The core building block. A data-processing module that you can think of as filter for data;
  3. Output Layer: Here we finally map to the desired output format;
  4. Loss function, which defines the feedback signal used for learning;
  5. Optimizer, which determines how learning proceeds.

Getting started with neural networks

  • Formally, a simple neural network can be represented as:

\[ \left[\begin{array} {r} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{array}\right] \longrightarrow \left[\begin{array} {r} a_1^{(2)} \\ a_2^{(2)} \\ a_3^{(2)} \end{array}\right] \longrightarrow \left[\begin{array} {r} a_1^{(3)} \\ a_2^{(3)} \\ a_3^{(3)} \end{array}\right] \longrightarrow h_{\theta}(x) \] where \(a_i^{(j)}\) is the activation unit \(i\) in layer \(j\);

  • Let \(\Theta^j\) the matrix of weights controling the mapping from layer \(j\) to layer \(j+1\)

\[ a_i^{(2)} = g(\Theta_{i0}^{(1)}x_0 + \Theta_{i1}^{(1)}x_1 + \Theta_{i2}^{(1)}x_2), \quad \text{for} \quad i = \{1, 2, 3\}\\ a_k^{(3)} = g(\Theta_{k0}^{(2)}a_0^{(2)} + \Theta_{k1}^{(2)}a_1^{(2)} + \Theta_{k2}^{(2)}a_2^{(2)} + \Theta_{k3}^{(2)}a_3^{(2)}), \quad \text{for} \quad k = \{1, 2, 3, 4\}\\ \]

where \(g(.)\) is an activation function, and

\[ h_\Theta(x) = g(\Theta_{10}^{(3)}a_0^{(3)} + \Theta_{11}^{(3)}a_1^{(3)} + \Theta_{12}^{(3)}a_2^{(3)} + \Theta_{13}^{(3)}a_3^{(3)}) \\ \]

Getting started with neural networks

  • Common choices for activation functions are:

    • Relu: \(g(x) = \max(o, x)\);
    • Sigmoid: \(g(x) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}}\);
    • Tanh: \(g(x) = \frac{2}{1 + e^{-2x}} - 1\)

  • But, what are activation functions and why are they necessary?

  • Without an activation function, the dense layer would consit of two linear operations;

  • Hence, the hypothesis space would be the set of all possible linear transformations;

  • In order to get access to much richer hypothesis space, we need some non-linearity.

Getting started with neural networks

  • The core building block of NN is the layer;

  • Some data goes in, and it comes out in a more useful form;

  • The matrix \(\Theta\) is responsible to map this transformation;

  • But how do we estimate the weights \(\theta_{i}^{(j)}\)?

  • Back-propagation algorithm:

  1. Draw a batch of training samples \(X\) and corresponding \(y\);
  2. Run the network on \(X\) (forward pass) to obtain predictions;
  3. Compute the loss of the network on the batch;
  4. Update all weights of the network in a way that reduces the loss on this batch (backward pass).

  • Deep learning models has achieved an impressive performance in perceptual problems:

    • Near-human-level image classification;
    • Near-human-level speech classification;
    • Near-human-level handwritting transcription;
    • Near-human-level autonomous driving;

  • Of course, Deep learning models are not always the best approach;

  • Sometimes, the simpler the better;
